WEBVTT

00:21.640 --> 00:25.360
X. Baker Farm.

00:27.340 --> 00:36.240
Sometimes I rambled to pine groves, standing like temples or like fleets at sea, full-rigged

00:36.240 --> 00:44.940
with wavy boughs and rippling with light, so soft and green and shady that the druids

00:44.940 --> 00:50.800
would have forsaken their oaks to worship in them, or to the cedar-wood beyond Flint's

00:50.800 --> 00:59.680
pond, where the trees, covered with hoary blue berries, spiring higher and higher, are

00:59.680 --> 01:06.880
fit to stand before Valhalla, and the creeping juniper covers the ground with wreaths full

01:06.880 --> 01:17.100
of fruit, or to swamps, where the Usnea lichen hangs in festoons from the white spruce trees

01:17.680 --> 01:27.560
and toadstools, round tables of the swamp gods, cover the ground, and more beautiful

01:27.560 --> 01:37.600
fungi adorn the stumps, like butterflies or shells, vegetable winkles, where the swamp

01:37.600 --> 01:47.800
pink and dogwood grow, the red alderberry glows like eyes of imps, the waxwork grooves

01:47.800 --> 01:57.040
and crushes the hardest woods in its folds, and the wild hollyberries make the beholder

01:57.040 --> 02:05.440
forget his home with their beauty, and he is dazzled and tempted by nameless other wild,

02:05.440 --> 02:16.700
forbidden fruits, too fair for mortal taste. Instead of calling on some scholar, I paid

02:16.700 --> 02:23.680
many a visit to particular trees, of kinds which are rare in this neighborhood, standing

02:23.680 --> 02:30.900
far away in the middle of some pasture, or in the depths of a wood or swamp, or on a

02:30.900 --> 02:38.980
hilltop, such as the black birch, of which we have some handsome specimens two feet in

02:38.980 --> 02:48.400
diameter, its cousin the yellow birch, with its loose golden vest, perfumed like the first,

02:49.360 --> 03:02.060
the beech, which has so neat a bowl, and beautifully lichen-painted, perfect in all its details,

03:02.880 --> 03:09.000
of which, excepting scattered specimens, I know but one small grove of sizable trees

03:09.000 --> 03:14.880
left in the township, supposed by some to have been planted by the pigeons that were

03:14.880 --> 03:22.980
once baited with beech nuts nearby. It is worth a while to see the silver grain sparkle

03:22.980 --> 03:35.960
when you split this wood, the bass, the hornbeam, the Celtis occidentalis, or false elm, of

03:35.960 --> 03:45.080
which we have but one well grown, some taller mast of a pine, a shingle-tree, or a more

03:45.080 --> 03:53.820
perfect hemlock than usual, standing like a pagoda in the midst of the woods, and many

03:53.820 --> 04:04.420
others I could mention. These were the shrines I visited, both summer and winter. Once it

04:04.420 --> 04:12.480
that I stood in the very abutment of a rainbow's arch, which filled the lower stratum of the

04:12.480 --> 04:22.080
atmosphere, tinging the grass and leaves around, and dazzling me as if I looked through colored

04:22.080 --> 04:33.340
crystal. It was a lake of rainbow light, in which, for a short while, I lived like a dolphin.

04:34.260 --> 04:42.040
If it had lasted longer it might have tinged my employments and life. As I walked on the

04:42.040 --> 04:49.760
railroad causeway I used to wonder at the halo of light around my shadow, and would

04:49.760 --> 04:56.100
vain fancy myself one of the elect. One who visited me declared that the shadows of some

04:56.100 --> 05:02.480
Irishman before him had no halo about them, that it was only natives that were so distinguished.

05:04.380 --> 05:12.640
Benvenuto Salini tells us in his memoirs that, after a certain terrible dream or vision which

05:12.640 --> 05:20.560
he had during his confinement in the castle of St. Angelo, a resplendent light appeared

05:20.560 --> 05:26.460
over the shadow of his head at morning and evening, whether he was in Italy or France,

05:26.760 --> 05:34.180
and it was particularly conspicuous when the grass was moist with dew. This was probably

05:34.180 --> 05:40.240
the same phenomenon to which I have referred, which is especially observed in the morning,

05:40.820 --> 05:47.560
but also at other times and even by moonlight, though a constant one it is not commonly noticed,

05:48.320 --> 05:54.700
and in the case of an excitable imagination like Salini's it would be basis enough for

05:54.700 --> 06:04.060
superstition. Beside, he tells us that he showed it to very few. But are they not indeed

06:04.060 --> 06:11.400
distinguished who are conscious that they are regarded at all? I set out one afternoon

06:11.400 --> 06:18.620
to go a-fishing to Fair Haven, through the woods, to eke out my scanty fare of vegetables.

06:18.620 --> 06:26.600
My way led through Pleasant Meadow, an adjunct of the baker-farm, that retreat of which a

06:26.600 --> 06:28.600
poet has since sung, beginning,

06:30.020 --> 06:35.660
Thy entry is a pleasant field, which some mossy fruit-trees yield,

06:36.480 --> 06:41.820
Partly to a ruddy brook, by gliding musquash undertook,

06:42.380 --> 06:45.700
And mercurial trout darting about.

06:46.500 --> 06:53.900
I thought of living there before I went to Walden. I hooked the apples, leaped the brook,

06:54.060 --> 07:02.040
and scared the musquash and the trout. It was one of those afternoons which seem indefinitely

07:02.040 --> 07:10.020
long before one, in which many events may happen, a large portion of our natural life,

07:10.020 --> 07:12.600
though it was already half spent when I started.

07:13.620 --> 07:20.720
By the way there came up a shower, which compelled me to stand half an hour under a pine, piling

07:20.720 --> 07:27.720
boughs over my head, and wearing my handkerchief for a shed. And when at length I had made

07:27.720 --> 07:34.820
one cast over the pickerel weed, standing up to my middle in water, I found myself suddenly

07:34.820 --> 07:40.360
the shadow of a cloud, and the thunder began to rumble with such emphasis that I could

07:40.360 --> 07:48.260
do no more than listen to it. The gods must be proud, thought I, with such forked flashes

07:48.260 --> 07:56.400
to rout a poor unarmed fisherman. So I made haste for shelter to the nearest hut, which

07:56.400 --> 08:02.420
stood half a mile from any road, but so much the nearer to the pond, and had long been

08:02.420 --> 08:11.460
inhabited. And here a poet builded, in the completed years, for behold a trivial cabin

08:11.460 --> 08:17.420
that two destructions steers. So the muse fables.

08:18.680 --> 08:26.420
But therein, as I found, dwelt now John Field, an Irishman, and his wife, and several children,

08:26.740 --> 08:31.880
from the broad-faced boy who assisted his father at his work, and now came running by

08:31.880 --> 08:39.520
aside from the bog to escape the rain, to the wrinkled, sibil-like, cone-headed infant

08:39.520 --> 08:45.740
that sat upon its father's knee as in the palaces of nobles, and looked out from its

08:45.740 --> 08:53.840
home in the midst of wet and hunger inquisitively upon the stranger, with the privilege of infancy,

08:54.630 --> 09:01.840
not knowing but it was the last of a noble line, and the hope and sinishure of the world,

09:02.540 --> 09:10.020
instead of John Field's poor, starvling brat. There we sat together, under that part of

09:10.020 --> 09:17.040
the roof which leaked the least, while it showered and thundered without. I had sat

09:17.040 --> 09:22.520
there many times of old before the ship was built that floated his family to America.

09:24.120 --> 09:33.080
An honest, hard-working, but shiftless man plainly was John Field, and his wife, she

09:33.080 --> 09:41.460
too was brave to cook so many successive dinners in the recesses of that lofty stove, with

09:42.040 --> 09:49.000
face and bare breast, still thinking to improve her condition one day, with the never-absent

09:49.000 --> 09:56.740
mop in one hand, and yet no effects of it visible anywhere. The chickens which had also

09:56.740 --> 10:03.600
taken shelter here from the rain stalked about the room like members of the family. Too humanized,

10:03.600 --> 10:10.240
me thought, to roast well. They stood and looked in my eye, or pecked at my shoe significantly.

10:12.140 --> 10:19.140
Meanwhile my host told me his story, how hard he worked bogging for a neighbouring farmer,

10:19.620 --> 10:25.440
turning up a meadow with a spade or bog hoe at the rate of ten dollars an acre, and the

10:25.440 --> 10:32.360
use of the land with manure for one year, and his little broad-faced son worked cheerfully

10:32.360 --> 10:38.300
at his father's side the while, not knowing how poor a bargain the latter had made.

10:39.820 --> 10:45.580
I tried to help him with my experience telling him that he was one of my nearest neighbours,

10:45.660 --> 10:51.640
and that I, too, who came a-fishing here, and looked like a loafer, was getting my living

10:51.640 --> 10:59.420
like himself, that I lived in a tight, light, and clean house, which hardly cost more than

10:59.420 --> 11:06.380
the annual rent of such a ruin as his commonly amounts to, and how, if he chose, he might

11:06.380 --> 11:13.280
in a month or two build himself a palace of his own, that I did not use tea, nor coffee,

11:13.420 --> 11:20.400
nor butter, nor milk, nor fresh meat, and so did not have to work to get them. Again,

11:21.000 --> 11:28.200
as I did not work hard, I did not have to eat hard, and it cost me but a trifle for

11:28.200 --> 11:37.660
my food. But as he began with tea, and coffee, and butter, and milk, and beef, he had to

11:37.660 --> 11:43.560
work hard to pay for them, and when he had worked hard, he had to eat hard again to repair

11:43.560 --> 11:50.940
the waste of his system. And so it was as broad as it was long. Indeed, it was broader

11:50.940 --> 11:59.480
long, for he was discontented and wasted his life into the bargain, and yet he had rated

11:59.480 --> 12:07.580
it as a gain in coming to America, that here you could get tea, and coffee, and meat every

12:07.580 --> 12:16.050
day. But the only true America is that country where you are at liberty to pursue such a

12:16.050 --> 12:25.690
of life as may enable you to do without these, and where the state does not endeavor to compel

12:25.690 --> 12:35.350
you to sustain the slavery, and war, and other superfluous expenses which directly or indirectly

12:35.350 --> 12:44.310
result from the use of such things. For I purposely talked to him as if he were a philosopher,

12:44.890 --> 12:52.210
or desired to be one. I should be glad if all the meadows on the earth were left in

12:52.210 --> 12:59.490
a wild state, if that were the consequence of men's beginning to redeem themselves.

13:01.530 --> 13:09.150
A man will not need to study history to find out what is best for his own culture, but,

13:09.150 --> 13:17.590
Alas! the culture of an Irishman is an enterprise to be undertaken with a sort of moral bog

13:17.590 --> 13:25.950
hoe. I told him that as he worked so hard at bogging he required thick boots and stout

13:25.950 --> 13:33.350
clothing, which yet were soon soiled and worn out, but I wore light shoes and thin clothing,

13:33.740 --> 13:39.270
which cost not half so much, though he might think that I was dressed like a gentleman,

13:40.190 --> 13:48.770
which however was not the case. And in an hour or two, without labor, but as a recreation,

13:49.830 --> 13:56.350
I could, if I wished, catch as many fish as I should want for two days, or earn enough

13:56.350 --> 14:04.150
to support me a week. If he and his family would live simply they might all go a huckle

14:04.150 --> 14:11.870
burying in the summer for their amusement. John heaved a sigh at this, and his wife stared

14:11.870 --> 14:18.990
with arms akimbo, and both appeared to be wondering if they had capital enough to begin

14:18.990 --> 14:27.130
such a course with, or arithmetic enough to carry it through. It was sailing by dead reckoning

14:27.130 --> 14:35.630
to them, and they saw not clearly how to make their port so. Therefore I suppose they still

14:35.630 --> 14:45.190
take life bravely, after their fashion, face to face, giving it tooth and nail, not having

14:45.190 --> 14:54.750
to split its massive columns with any fine entering wedge, and rout it in detail, thinking

14:54.750 --> 15:03.370
to deal with it roughly, as one should handle a thistle. But they fight at an overwhelming

15:03.370 --> 15:14.150
disadvantage. Living, John field, alas, without arithmetic, and failing so.

15:14.550 --> 15:22.070
"'Do you ever fish?' I asked. "'Oh, yes, I catch a mess now, and then, when I'm lying

15:22.070 --> 15:29.670
by, good perch I catch.' "'What's your bait?' "'I catch shiners with fish-worms, and bait

15:29.670 --> 15:36.770
the perch with them.' "'You'd better go now, John,' said his wife, with glistening

15:36.770 --> 15:44.630
and hopeful face. But John demurred. The shower was now over, and a rainbow above the eastern

15:44.630 --> 15:51.230
woods promised a fair evening, so I took my departure. When I had got without I asked

15:51.230 --> 15:57.150
for a drink, hoping to get a sight of the well bottom to complete my survey of the premises.

15:57.150 --> 16:08.030
But there, alas, are shadows and quicksands, and rope broken withal, and bucket irrecoverable.

16:08.990 --> 16:16.550
Meanwhile, the right culinary vessel was selected, water was seemingly distilled, and after consultation

16:16.550 --> 16:24.530
and long delay passed out to the thirsty one. Not yet suffered to cool, not yet to settle.

16:25.490 --> 16:32.710
Such gruel sustains life here, I thought. So, shutting my eyes, and excluding the moats

16:32.710 --> 16:40.530
by a skillfully directed undercurrent, I drank to genuine hospitality the heartiest draft

16:40.530 --> 16:48.530
I could. I am not squeamish in such cases when manners are concerned. As I was leaving

16:48.530 --> 16:56.030
the Irishman's roof after the rain, bending my steps again to the pond, my haste to catch

16:56.030 --> 17:04.610
Pickerel, wading in retired meadows, in sloughs and bog holes, in forlorn and savage places,

17:05.710 --> 17:12.650
appeared for an instant trivial to me who had been sent to school and college. But as

17:12.650 --> 17:19.870
I ran down the hill toward the reddening west, with a rainbow over my shoulder, and some

17:19.870 --> 17:26.830
faint tinkling sounds borne to my ear through the cleansed air, from I know not what quarter,

17:27.650 --> 17:31.150
my good genius seemed to say,

17:31.940 --> 17:45.170
Go fish and hunt, far and wide, day by day, farther and wider, and rest thee by many brooks

17:45.170 --> 17:54.790
and hearth-sides without misgiving. Remember thy Creator in the days of thy youth. Rise

17:54.790 --> 18:04.470
free from care before the dawn, and seek adventures. Let the noon find thee by other lakes, and

18:04.470 --> 18:13.710
the night overtake thee everywhere at home. There are no larger fields than these, no

18:13.710 --> 18:23.150
worthier games than may here be played. Grow wild according to thy nature, like these sedges

18:23.150 --> 18:32.610
and breaks, which will never become English Bay. Let the thunder rumble. What if it threaten

18:32.610 --> 18:41.570
ruin to farmers' crops? That is not its errand to thee. Take shelter under the cloud, while

18:41.570 --> 18:51.890
they flee to carts and sheds. Let not to get a living be thy trade, but thy sport. Enjoy

18:51.890 --> 19:02.310
the land, but own it not. Through want of enterprise and faith, men are where they are,

19:02.870 --> 19:10.390
buying and selling, and spending their lives like serfs.

19:11.270 --> 19:23.190
O Baker Farm! Landscape where the richest element is a little sunshine innocent. No

19:23.190 --> 19:32.910
one runs to revel on thy rail-fenced lee. Debate with no man hast thou. With questions

19:32.910 --> 19:42.370
art never perplexed, as tame at the first sight as now, in thy plain russet gabardine

19:42.370 --> 19:53.210
dressed. Come ye who love, and ye who hate, children of the holy dove, and Guy Fow of

19:53.210 --> 20:03.430
the state, and hang conspiracies from the tough rafters of the trees. Men come tamely

20:03.430 --> 20:11.130
home at night, only from the next field or street, where their household echoes haunt,

20:11.350 --> 20:19.450
and their life pines because it breathes its own breath over again. Their shadows morning

20:19.450 --> 20:28.750
and evening reach farther than their daily steps. We should come home from far, from

20:28.750 --> 20:40.450
adventures and perils and discoveries every day, with new experience and character. Before

20:40.450 --> 20:47.930
I had reached the pond some fresh impulse had brought out John Field, with altered mind,

20:48.700 --> 20:59.330
letting go bogging ere this sunset. But he, poor man, disturbed only a couple of fins

20:59.330 --> 21:06.170
while I was catching a fair string, and he said it was his luck. But when we changed

21:06.170 --> 21:15.010
seats in the boat luck changed seats too. Poor John Field! I trust he does not read

21:15.010 --> 21:23.310
this, unless he will improve by it, thinking to live by some derivative old country mode

21:23.310 --> 21:33.490
in this primitive new country, to catch perch with shiners. It is good bait sometimes, I

21:33.490 --> 21:45.570
know. With this horizon all his own, yet he, a poor man, born to be poor, with his

21:45.570 --> 21:56.090
inherited Irish poverty or poor life, his Adam's grandmother and boggy ways, not to

21:56.090 --> 22:06.250
in this world. He nor his posterity, till their wading webbed bog trotting feet, get

22:06.250 --> 22:08.070
to their heels.

